<small>time reversing and little kids are screaming out to their mommies.
drop those needles even though they're clean baby doll you don't need that junk no more.
beautiful stones roll down those green green hills and nothing but the sounds of birds will wake you.
let it all slide down let it all wash down with a cold glass of something pure and maybe you can hear the waterfalling splish splashing outside your window clear
window fogged
window glass.
if you're asking me questions i'll just have to nod and deliver you everything as it comes as it falls out of my jumbled head and into the air before me, let it's kiss hit your ears and leave the lipstick marks across the skin.
it won't burn i promise.
i'm too nice to ever hurt you. but i'll certainly confuse you, oh i'm sorry things won't make much sense.
but if you stop looking for the sense in all of this then maybe you'll see how beautiful and wonderful and magical everything really is despite the horrible things you'd see if you'd turn your head around.
so don't. just look at me. just let it all wash down with a glass of water and put your face to the cool of the window glass you fogged with your heavy sobbing breath.
it will be ok, it will be alright.
just listen carefully and let me be your guide-dog.
i'm sorry it can't make more sense.

Best Dear John Letter Ever 

A Marine stationed in Afghanistan recently received a "Dear John" letter 
from his girlfriend back home. It read as follows: 

Dear Ricky, I can no longer continue our relationship. The distance between 
us is just too great. I must admit that I have cheated on you twice, since 
you've been gone, and it's not fair to either of us. I'm sorry. Please 
return the picture of me that I sent to you. Love, Becky 

The Marine, with hurt feelings, asked his fellow Marines for any snapshots 
they could spare of their girlfriends, sisters, ex-girlfriends, aunts, 
cousins etc. In addition to the picture of Becky, Ricky included all the 
other pictures of the pretty gals he had collected from his buddies. There 
were 57 photos in that envelope....along with this note: 

Dear Becky, I'm so sorry, bu t I can't quite remember who the F*** you are. 
Please take your picture from the pile, and send the rest back to me. Take 
Care, Ricky

so thats what i came up with originally. then it turned into a poem.
~
This is all just a line in some cliche divine book.
I'm broken, I've been bleeding
But all I am is yours. 
there is nothing in my way this time
and nothing in your headlights but an empty road and feelings that you can't give up.
so keep driving
hold on
and all of this will be worthwhile.
there are some things that are worth the pain
worth all the blood that is swept under the bridge
and this is one of them
so keep driving
you've got nothing in your headlights
all you've got is an empty road and feelings that i won't let you give up.
fingers dancing across keys and bringing the music for tonight
staring up into a sky as song flows out of my everything.
you're making me sing, making me ignore the buzzing in my ear
and all i can do is think of how lucky i am
so we'll keep driving
there's nothing in our headlights and nothing on this road
i won't let go if you won't
and we'll keep this empty road to ourselves and watch the night sky fly by
all i am is yours
and all we are is stars in the sky,
we just happened to collide.
~september  7, 2004

Things you have to believe to be a Republican today:

Saddam was a good guy when Reagan armed him, a bad guy when Bush's daddy
made war on him, a good guy when Cheney did business with him and a bad guy 
when Bush needed a "we can't find Bin Laden" diversion.

Trade with Cuba is wrong because the country is communist, but trade with 
China and Vietnam is vital to a spirit of international harmony.

The United States should get out of the United Nations, and our highest 
national priority is enforcing U.N. resolutions against Iraq.

A woman can't be trusted with decisions about her own body, but 
multi-national corporations can make decisions affecting all mankind 
without regulation.

Jesus loves you, and shares your hatred of homosexuals and Hillary 
Clinton.

The best way to improve military morale is to praise the troops in 
speeches while slashing veterans' benefits and combat pay.

If condoms are kept out of schools, adolescents won't have sex.

A good way to fight terrorism is to belittle our long-time allies, then 
demand their cooperation and money.

Providing health care to all Iraqis is sound policy. Providing health 
care to all Americans is socialism.

HMOs and insurance companies have the best interests of the public at 
heart.

Global warming and tobacco's link to cancer are junk science, but 
creationism should be taught in schools.

A president lying about an extramarital affair is a impeachable 
offense.

A president lying to enlist support for a war in which thousands die is 
solid defense policy.

Government should limit itself to the powers named in the Constitution, 
which include banning gay marriages and censoring the Internet.

The public has a right to know about Hillary's cattle trades, but George 
Bush's driving record is none of our business.

Being a drug addict is a moral failing and a crime, unless you're a 
conservative radio host. Then it's an illness, and you need our prayers 
for your recovery.

You support states' rights, which means Attorney General John Ashcroft can 
tell states what local voter initiatives they have the right to adopt.

What Bill Clinton did in the 1960s is of vital national interest, but what 
Bush did in the '80s is irrelevant.

Feel free to pass this on. 

If you don't post it in your own journals and communities, we're likely to be 
stuck with Bush for 4 more years.

Friends don't let friends vote Republican.

i found a poem i wrote last year, it sounds kinda like a song that i read not too long ago. odd that they would be so similar. but i dont remember the song so yeah. Seventeen Good morning, today i am seventeen, so i bought myself a chainsaw and seventeen new reasons to hate you. but i, though cold, could never hate you, so beautiful Can't you remember watching the sunrise? Listening to the buzz of a cheap phone and your steady breaths. I stared out my window and you stared out yours, Today I am seventeen. now here's this year's birthday. Eighteen Here comes the sunrise, yesterday was my last day of seventeen. Sleep has escaped me and I fear I will not wake up feeling one year older. So I'll buy myself the snow and another night without sleep, and eighteen more reasons to hate you, and maybe this. I'll pull in my breath and think to myself how much I honestly love you. Because I, though cold, could never hate you, so beautiful. I'll stare out my window with my foot against the gas, you'll do the same. Today I am eighteen.

I'm lost and I love it. I can't take it, if you're waiting. I am ready to tell the world about a girl who showed me love again for the first time. And it's everything I dreamed of. this is what bush said in a speech yesterday: "our enemies are innovative and resourceful, and so are we. they never stop trying to find new ways to harm our country and our people, and neither do we." what a retard. and now, for your pleasure, something i haven't done in a while! the posting of a depressing poem! Boy Girl He is a boy. And no one is home. Never is, and seems like there never will be. He can't see through his baby blues Theyre squeezed shut, squeezing out his deepest wishes, fears, dreams. Evaporate before they hit the floor No love has ever been borne on the end of a bullet At the end of a rope. Only arrows from a little boy who does not exist. Seventeen years wishing only for that arrow From anyone, for anything He is a boy, And no one is home. Nor will there be. All alone he tastes that which has never been fired His baby blues squeezing out his greatest wishes. And his fears. Shaky now, can't lose his courage All alone, He is a boy. And that fire means just that. He is a boy, And always will be. She is a girl, Holding onto a blackened rainbow Candles in her room to dim the lights Burn her reflection dulled, opaque attempt at perfection. She feels so weak She's skin and bone Nothing to hold but a ribcage and limbs Yellowed teeth show her faith in a porcelain god to which she kneels and leaves prayers and offerings torn from deep within her. She wants to be beautiful She cries, tries to be beautiful. Her chocolate eyes swim in an ocean of lonely Lost forever. She is a girl, Holding onto her hair and her blackened rainbow. No ugliness has ever been borne in a bathtub, Nor has any love. No violence, Only perfect solitude. Raazor thin veins run through her tiny wrists Weakened, barely able to run away. Bathwater so hued to make a stop sign turn green Enviable courage while she's breaking her skin Twisted smiles or looks of remorse As her chocolate eyes go swimming She is a girl Holding onto her blackened metallic rainbow Drowning now but not gasping for air All the color from her once rosy cheeks now floating about her She is light, no spirit to drag her down She bites her tongue, she is free She is a girl, And always will be. Rejected a thousand tomorrows Fragile smiles gone away, For them there will never be a today. Troubles within through their eyes Are no more Glassy eyes and cold skin Never finding the warmth they needed Instead they have run away And now they are free. He is a boy, She is a girl. And forever they will stay that way.

hmm...
some thoughts prang to mind after reading close_the_door's journal. someone died on sunday. and it was very very sudden.
and reading what she wrote about celebrating everything she has has made me think. i mean, i have been celebrating everything i have and attempting to live my life to it's fullest as much as i can, enjoying everything that life has to offer and what not, but am i really truly living it?
i mean, what am i doing with myself?
i might just drop tomorrow and have accomplished nothing.
on the upside of all thise philosophical stuff i talked to some of the old people at the personal care home today on my first day of work. it was definately an experience. i had a conversation in french with a lady who might just be crazy, but at the same time i know she has seen alot and what she's seen will still show through in her eyes. and some of the things that an old man told me today kind of made me realise just how lucky i am. i also talked to a kid about my age with downs syndrome. he is always so happy and personable. it makes me smile to know that someone who knows so little can be so happy with himself. he's such a great kid.
i dont know. maybe it's the fact that i've been pretty introspective lately, maybe it's the fact that things have been happening to make me think, or maybe it's the fact that i finally found some sort of something to believe in, but i've been appreciating the little things alot more lately. aaah life is good. i may not have a significant other, or be doing exactly what i want to be doing, but i'm still living one day at a time and i'm happy.
that's more than i could ask for.
so whomever reads this, take some advice from me.
enjoy everything you have. even if you think everything is shit. it probably isnt all that bad.
smile at someone you don't know. 
and for goodness sakes, if you're rude to people you don't know, stop it. everyone be nice to everyone today.
it's made me a lot happier.

celebrate everything.
and remember that i love each and every one of you.
<3
